experiment_description:
Cells go through an activation phase (~25 h), followed by a brief phase to initialize molecules for the cell cycle.
Cells then transition into a centroblast state where they upregulate CXCR4 receptor and migrate to the Dark Zone.While in the centroblast state, cells undergo ~10 cell divisions (~ 6 h cell cycle time) before transitioning to centrocytes.
Centrocytes down-regulate CXCR4 receptor and upregulate CXCR5 receptor, causing them to migrate to the Light Zone.Centrocytes are rescued and transition back to centroblasts with a mean time of 6 h.
The E1 molecule that drives the transition out to the G0 cell cycle phase is renewed after centrocyte rescue, but at a lower level than after activation, so rescued cells undergo ~2-3 rounds of division.
Centrocytes that transition into the apoptotic state upregulate production of the sApop molecule which drives cell death.The mean time for removal of dead cells from the simulation is 15 h.

Light Zone: 
Gaussian distribution of CXCL13 centered in the simulation space
coordinates=(130, 130, 130), standard deviations=200

Dark Zone
Gaussian distribution of CXCL12 centered in the upper right corner of the simulation space
coordinates=(222, 222, 222), standard deviation=100

reaction_complexes.description: A set of reactions that are needed by GC B cells for chemotaxis. These reactions should be added to the cytosol. The magnitude and direction of the chemotactic force is proportional to the polarization of activated pseudo-molecule A*, which is proportional to the polarization of bound chemokine receptors (CXCL12:CXCR4| and CXCL13:CXCR5|).

reaction_complexes.description: Goldbeter A, Koshland DE. An amplified sensitivity arising from covalent modification in biological systems. Proc Natl Acad Sci USA 1981, 78:6840-6844.With these parameter choices and W_total=W+Wp >> E1_total and E2_total, the reactions will produce switch-like behavior for W and Wp around the point when E1_total/E2_total=1.

reaction_complexes.description: A set of transcription reactions needed to synthesize the molecules for the Goldbeter-Koshland switch reactions. sDif1 catalyzes the annihilation of E1. This can be used after the centroblast/centrocyte transition to arrest the cell cycle at the G0 phase.

Cell.description:
This cell has a 10 um diameter and undergoes stochastic locomotion.  
The plasma membrane has CXCR4 and CXCR5 receptors which are homeostatically maintained through gene transcription, transport to the plasma membrane, internalization, and degrdation. CXCR4 and CXCR5 production rates are based on data from de Guinoa et al. (2011). CXCR4 and CXCR5 receptor interanlization rates are based on data from Barrosso et al. (2012) and Hesselgesser et al. (1998). 
The cell moves chemotactically in the presence of CXCL12 or CXCL13 gradients. The (pseudo) molecule A* is the chemotaxis 'driver': the chemotactic force is proportional to the gradient of [A*], which is induced by gradients in bound chemokine receptors (CXCL12:CXCR4| and CXCL13:CXCR5|). 
The cell has the following behaviors: 
Differentiation states: activated, pre-centroblast, centroblast, centrocyte, rescued, apoptotic
Division (cell cycle) states: G0, G1, S, G2-M, cytokinetic
Death (after reaching apoptotic state)

reaction_complexes.description: A set of reactions that are needed by GC B cells for chemotaxis. These cells should be added to the ECM. Non-uniform distributions of ligand (CXCL13 and CXCL12) in the ECM will cause non-uniform concentrations of bound chemokine receptors (CXCR5| and CXCR4|) and non-uniform distributions of the pseudo-molecule A*. The magnitude and direction of the chemotactic force is proportional to the polarization of activated pseudo-molecule A*, which is proportional to the polarization of bound chemokine receptors (CXCL12:CXCR4| and CXCL13:CXCR5|).
